.TH "HTMLInputElement.select" "JS" "April 7, 2023" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
HTMLInputElement.select \- HTMLInputElement: select() method
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]HTMLInputElement.select()\f[B]\f[R] method selects all
the text in a \f[CR]<textarea>\f[R] element or in an \f[CR]<input>\f[R]
element that includes a text field.
.SH SYNTAX
.IP
.EX
select()
.EE
.SS Parameters
None.
.SS Return value
None (\f[CR]undefined\f[R]).
.SH EXAMPLES
Click the button in this example to select all the text in the
\f[CR]<input>\f[R] element.
.SS HTML
.IP
.EX
<input type=\[dq]text\[dq] id=\[dq]text\-box\[dq] size=\[dq]20\[dq] value=\[dq]Hello world!\[dq] />
<button onclick=\[dq]selectText()\[dq]>Select text</button>
.EE
.SS JavaScript
.IP
.EX
function selectText() {
  const input = document.getElementById(\[dq]text\-box\[dq]);
  input.focus();
  input.select();
}
.EE
.SS Result
.SH NOTES
Calling \f[CR]element.select()\f[R] will not necessarily focus the
input, so it is often used with \f[CR]HTMLElement.focus\f[R].
.PP
In browsers where it is not supported, it is possible to replace it with
a call to HTMLInputElement.setSelectionRange() with parameters 0 and the
input\[cq]s value length:
.IP
.EX
<input onClick=\[dq]this.select();\[dq] value=\[dq]Sample Text\[dq] />
<!\-\- equivalent to \-\->
<input
  onClick=\[dq]this.setSelectionRange(0, this.value.length);\[dq]
  value=\[dq]Sample Text\[dq] />
.EE
